I’m not a “car guy.” But I have an architecture/photography/design background and have long appreciated Japanese design. I didn’t own a car for a decade but always loved 40 and 60 Cruisers. They were the only car that caused pause in my life.

(I still believe the bicycle is the best mode of transport for commuting, errands, and exploring places; for trips short and long but here we are in a system built around autos.)

My first Cruiser was a HJ61, then a HDJ81, and now I have an HJ75 (technically a RJ75 with the Cummins R2.8) - yet these old 40s still captivate me.

I prefer to use our Troopy as a means to get deeper, further into the places we love to then backpack, bike tour, rock hound, do drugs and get away from the modern world.

The Japanese metal company Toyoda introduced their version of the flat fender Willys in June 1950 for the Korean War but added with it refined proportions, better engineering, and longevity.

Hanging at @olc4x4 with @onur.azeri.olc4x4 as he gets the 75 tidied up for a Baja trip, I’ve been nerding out on these old 40s. One day I’d love to own one but one shitbox is enough right now…

I’ve been slowly moving through the Troopy, overhauling drivetrain components, and doing maintenance over the past few years but aside from the engine swap, this was the most crucial bit of work.

@onur.azeri.olc4x4 went though the front and rear axles and brakes, taking out the mismatched Aussie bush fixes and restoring everything back to OE standards. The Troopy has a later HZJ LSD FF rear axle so now both axles are set up with early USDM 80 series rotors and calipers. It actually stops now. 😋

Then, we bypassed the load sensing valve to give the brakes 50/50 rather than 60/40 braking power. Since the rear of the car is going to be as heavy as the front when we’re loaded with bikes and 40g of fuel, this was important…

We replaced the entire parking brake assembly and added a first gen 80 series brake booster and master cylinder.

I can now stop within 20’ on a gravel road from 55mph and much less, about 10’, on pavement. I don’t go 55mph on dirt roads usually so this is great news!

Many thanks to @onur.azeri.olc4x4 and @olc4x4 for knocking this job out. 

We also added a 40 gallon @longrangeamerica tank to the rear and fixed my rear bumper so the bike rack doesn’t sag anymore…

I tell people this all the time. Say you spent $40k on a Troopy (not what I paid at all) - expect to sink another $20k into maintenance off the bat…

I love going places with a 50mm Summilux lens on my M10 and just framing compositions for a few hours.

For the past year, I’ve been using the @espressoforge and couldn’t be happier. I was content with my Aeropress (I first bought mine in 2010!) but always wanted an in-home espresso machine.

To buy a good espresso machine is thousands of dollars and the ones I wanted require service every year and a hard line for water. Plus they take up so much space. Our kitchen doesn’t have enough counter top space for a machine.

When I met the guys from Espresso Forge in Colorado in 2021, they showed me their new Forge, which uses the same principles as a counter top machine, at a drastic reduction in price and spacial requirements.

The most crucial element is the grind of your beans. I use a Lido OG grinder to get the beans to an espresso grind. 19g tampered in a basket that threads into the bottom of the press.

I use a Snowpeak mug that nests perfectly with the Forge, but Espresso Forge makes a stand as well.

You pour boiling water into the chamber, press to 140psi (just like a counter top maker) and voila, out comes a beautiful crema.

The kit is relatively compact and I bring it on the road, that way I don’t have to rely on the locale having good spro. I can just make it myself. Camping, hotels, whatever.

I love made in the USA product and the rad people behind them. 

Espresso Forge sent me one to try out since I’m friends with them, at no obligation, and I offered to shoot some photos and post about it after using it for some time.

I don’t get paid for this stuff, it’s all from the heart, so thanks. 🖤🤘🏻

I’d love to see more sustainable planning, PV arrays on every house, and less optimizing for cars, creating safer cycling and pedestrian infrastructure because your fancy Tesla is unobtainable for most Americans.

Humans are resilient and creative and while those changes might not happen in our lifetimes, I’d like to think it’s in our nature to make our homes and cities more comfortable. 

As climate change alters these landscapes and the cities beholden to them, it won’t be an option or a environmentalist fantasy, it will have to become a reality.

Nighttime Snacks.

We started storing our food in a 18” tall Rubbermade bin. It keeps chips from getting crushed by duffel bags and makes figuring out what to snack on a lot easier. Yet we do it for other reasons too.

We store this bin and another bin filled with firewood on Max’s old bed platform. They lock perfectly in place.

I like this system because the bins are removed when we get to camp, freeing up the interior space of the car. I don’t like Troopy setups with big cabinets because I like the openness they can feel like when done more minimally. 

The procession of taking things out of the car to cook and be outside is really important to the feeling of being camping. Otherwise, it’d be like an RV. All this is just preference, of course. 

For me, the pop top is for sleeping and the car can act as a tent itself when we’re camping. If it’s windy, rainy, or really cold, we’ll escape to the tent. But we prefer to be doing everything outside.

After a few days, we’ll pack up and head out, leaving nothing but tire tracks, and packing out any trash we found upon arrival.

This is the first build with @8020llc I’ve done for someone other than myself.

I’m spending the week with @jweinberg to work on some bike reviews for @theradavist and last weekend we tackled this super simple 8020 build for his F150 with a GFC.

He wanted a fridge slide with space for his stove and a few camp chairs underneath. Then a big 6’2” long sleeping platform (he has a cushion for the sleeping platform) with space for his 12V battery, and two @frontrunneroutfitters Wolf Packs.

We bolted some 1/2” ply to the bed, then put a thick mat over that and bolted the 80/20 to the ply, via some 90° brackets. 

I think people tend to get too complicated with this sort of thing and most people can get away with a minimal setup like this. It took some problem solving but the solutions are clean and the final product is both lightweight and transforms the space. Plus, he can still haul material in the bed.

What’s great about this system is if he ever decides he wants some drawers or a modification, it’s really easy to do. All in the sleeping platform weighs 18 ish pounds and the fridge cabinet is 35 lbs (including the empty fridge) mostly due to the heavy duty locking Ovis drawer slides we used.
I can do this all day…

Every bike ride is an inspiration here. Big 🖤, Arizona.

Yesterday I finished the refresh on the driver’s side cabinet in the Troopy. I used @8020llc 10 series, Accuride touch latch drawer slides, and a HD locking slide for the tool drawer.

This cabinet has (2) 20x20x9” food drawers, a 38x14x9” tool drawer and a large 38x18x14” storage cubby on the top with a touch latch drop down working surface out of 1/2” bamboo.

I also re-upped our House battery to 200ah with a 2000w inverter (200a fuse) so Cari can use the @conwayelectric outlet and an electric kettle to make tea while we’re driving.

These projects can drag on if you’re not making a drawing of what you’re building. My Rhino 3D model helped me figure out all sorts of details and I doubt this would be as dialed if I couldn’t problem solve in 3D first. The Troopy cargo area has a lot of shaping, and putting a big box in it presents some difficulties (the top half tapers inward and the stud wall has a slight taper to it as well.)

Also, I love the orange bungees! @jweinberg had a scrap orange yoga mat I used for the shelf padding too.

All in, both sides of the buildout, minus things like the Webasto cabin heater, batteries, inverter, and fridge cost me around $3000. Which isn’t bad at all! But if you were paying a shop labor ($75-$150/hr depending on where you live) it can quickly double or triple that number. Where’s the fun in that? This stuff is so easy to use and is incredibly strong and lightweight.

There are plenty of YouTube videos walking you through 80/20 basics, like use a non-ferrous Diablo blade to get clean cuts, so if you’re going to try this, watch those. If you have a Sprinter or E Series van, I’d recommend the 15 or 20 series, but in smaller spaces or the back of a pickup  like this where every inch matters, 10 series works great, just support any span longer than 24”….

I’m glad this is “done.” I have a few little quirks I have to work out with the touch slides but it’s super secure and now when we travel there won’t be bags everywhere…

Cari and I haven’t traveled internationally since 2017. We just booked tickets to go see her brother in France and to do a proper “honeymoon.”

We’ve been such desert rats over the years but it’s time to put the canyons, buttes, mesas, and dust on the side and get out to find beauty in man made structures.

My two favorite trips we’ve been on were London and Japan. We spent a few weeks traveling around Japan on boats and trains and hoping to do the same in Europe. No bikes, just a rangefinder and two lenses…

You know what? I’m tired. Not sleepy but just tired. It’s exhausting to perpetually crank out content for a full time job. Since 2006, I’ve documented cycling culture and now, 17 years later, I’m still doing it, albeit at a higher standard (IMO.)

The landscape has changed in this time. The proliferation of social media changed the cadence in which we produce work. Suddenly, everyone is shooting events on their phones and it’s caused us to go into overdrive at @theradavist to keep up. 

We have to keep on our toes. Finding a line between keeping up with tech and trends while reflecting on the progression of cycling for the past 40 years. Not to mention other sites straight up copying our very unique style and the look/feel of our special website.

It’s easy to get wrapped up in the churn and burn media cycle but damn, I still love shooting bicycles and it will always take me to a special place within my own psyche to document one of my own builds.

It’s cathartic to take a frame and build it up, scouring the ‘net for parts, adding some personal touches and making a ridable work of art.

Instagram and the internet are always looking forward, towards the new, the latest, etc and that’s a big reason why I feel like I’ve gotten burnt out over the years.

Yet I’ve had a lot of fun lately taking on a select few restoration projects.

I feel as creatives, we have to respect our past work to keep our heads on a level plane and to progress/push our limits. I look back at the previous year’s work to determine where I want to steer the ship in the coming year with my team. If someone is copying our stuff, we’ll just evolve, stay ahead.

I really value my co-workers, @hailey.m.moore and @jweinberg and everyone else who helps out on the site (too many to list but you know who you are!) and I feel really good about where we are at @theradavist.

There will always be biters, haters, and those who plant flags and claim things as their own. We’ll just be busy doing our own shit in the meantime. The Radavist has inspired and influenced the cycling industry for the past decade+ and I don’t see that changing.

Thanks for following along…

social_posts.post_text:
Seeing the Eileen Grey E1027 building in Cap Moderne was high on my list. She was an architect in the 1920s who designed this house in her 50s, being inspired by Corbusier, who later visited the Mediterranean and met Eileen.

There’s a long, convoluted history surrounding this house, Eileen’s life, and Corb’s Le Cabanon home (where he died in 1965) - which I highly recommend you look up.

As such I’ll be sharing the Corbusier work separately in another post, giving Eileen’s work its own light.

She invented the sliding shutters, even had a patent for them, sculpted space with planes and line of sight, and pulled inspiration from her trans-Atlantic travels, maritime design, and a love for the Mediterranean.

If you find yourself in the area, buy tickets for this tour. It’s well worth it.

🤍

#eileengrey #capmoderne #e1027 #corbusier

The poor air quality (mix of wind born dust from Africa - cc @krstina.young - and pollution) made for a pretty ok sunset - albeit some strange streaking in the sky - the other night as the light reflected off the Cap Canaille…

Our trip in Southern France has come to an end. Au Revoir, France!

social_posts.post_text:
Anyone who is even remotely interested in design should read ‘Towards a New Architecture’ - between Corbusier and Rem Koolhaas’ writings, my perspective on the built landscape was forever changed.

I mentioned in my previous post about Corb’s tenuous relationship with Eileen Grey and the E1027 house. He painted a few murals - without permission - that Eileen felt distracted from the strong design elements of E1027. One of which, a nude of a woman, was on the entryway door…

Corbusier passed away in 1965 while swimming in the Mediterranean from a heart attack. He spent the last years of his life in Cap Moderne, painting, writing, and swimming in this inspirational place.

Corb designed four cabins in a row with colorful façades behind the E1027 property to rent to travelers. These roughly 10x10’ cabins were the right amount of space for weary tourists.

Seeing Le Cabanon, his personal cabin, in person was a lifelong dream. The parti of his cabin makes efficient use of the small space. I studied it in architecture school.

Unfortunately no photos were allowed inside but I was able to shoot some of these small cabins with the Modulor Man on the side…

I came back from France super tan. Living at 7000’, the UV radiation is often extreme (yesterday was a UV index of 13!!!), so I’m usually covering my arms and head with UL hoodies or western shirts and a bandana, while being mindful of using waterproof sunblock on my face and ears - especially after battling skin cancer.

Yet having a safe base tan is good for you and keeps you from burning if you slip up with coverage. I loved going to the beach in the late afternoon when the sun was low - or laying out on rocks - and sun bathing for an hour or two each day. After two weeks of that, my body has a healthy bronze.

The UV radiation is considerably lower at sea level and having extra vitamin D felt amazing.

I grew up on the ocean in NC and yet for the better part of my adult life, I’ve wanted to be in mountains and deserts but man, there’s something majestic about swimming in the open ocean.

NOS 5 speed Suntour “alpine” gearing freewheel going on the 1980 Ritchey with matching gold Ukai rims.

I love how simple a 5-speed kit with TA Cyclotouriste 46/26 cranks is. Friction shifting Suntour Mighty shifters with a Huret mech and Comp V front derailleur was the height of MTB tech in the late 70s/early 80s until Deerhead came out in 1983.

There was more innovation in mountain biking in the three years leading up to ‘83 than we’ve seen in the past 30 years. Everything recent feels like a movement towards dirt bikes and moto culture.

Even though the founders of MTBing were using moto brakes and bars, the spirit of the movement was pushing yourself and your bike into the mountains… what a novel concept for a bicycle.

In September 2017 I recognized that alcohol was ruining my life. It was controlling me and jeopardized my relationship with Cari. September 7th, 2017 is when I quit altogether, cold turkey. 

(My doctor had also told me my kidneys and liver were in rough shape and would only be alive for less than a year if I kept at it. 😮)

Putting down the bottle was a hard move and in the process of quitting, I found out who my true friends were. 

Quitting drinking is bound to bring out your alcoholic friends’ insecurities and that’s the most difficult part about it. People will do anything to get you to drink because it makes them feel better about their problem. 

If you’re trying to cut back or quit drinking all together, I highly suggest surrounding yourself with people who will support your decision.

Alcohol abuse is an accepted thing in society. But that doesn’t mean you have to be a part of it.

Thanks to my mates who were there for me during that time. You know who you are. 🫶🏻⚔️🖤

(Also, therapy and AA are great resources for addiction treatment and highly recommended. Mocktails, NA beer, HopWater all help too!)

A mountain touring bike with good racks is like a 4x4 with good bar work. While sliders and bumpers serve a different purpose, I love seeing how racks also compliment a bike’s frame lines.

This 1983 @ritcheylogic Everest came with the “Touring Package” from Tom; Front and rear rack bosses.

Over the last few weeks I’ve tracked down NOS Jim Blackburn racks for it. Both the rear and the front are from the early 1980s.

The front is harder to find and features a “wrap around” fork crown attachment. You also have to bend the front stays to clear a MTB tire (I did it with a wood block and mallet) but the rack contours perfectly to the fork’s lines.

Once the paint has finished curing on the frame (probably another week or so) I’ll load it up and take it out on an overnighter under the changing Aspen trees…

Some missing moments (I got too distracted to document the whole process) but here’s our favorite camp dinner…

Make some classic meat chili. We like adding squash, zucchini, bell pepper, onion, and jalapeño to the bison meat.

Cook it in a Dutch Oven then add cornbread mix once the chili is done. Just pour mix in on top of the chili.

Take it off the stove, put it on some campfire coals, place some coals on the top of the Dutch Oven. Turn the whole pot a quarter turn clockwise every 5 minutes for 20 minutes.

Remove it from the fire and the cornbread absorbs the chili into a deliciously warm dinner for those cold winter nights…
